{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:13:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.27,0.22,0.18,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103500"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2710"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85922"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"351"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3410"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3452"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4612"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17727"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36037"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36486"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36547"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44088"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103500","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103500"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA four-day-old neonate, born at 38 weeks gestation, presents to the Emergency Department with episodes of central cyanosis occurring shortly after direct breastfeeding. The baby\u0027s parent did not receive any antenatal care. The baby has no significant medical history and takes no medications. On examination, the neonate appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no tachypnoea and no evidence of central or peripheral cyanosis. No other abnormalities are found.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe neonate is admitted to the ward and remains clinically stable, with normal observations overnight. A chest X-ray shows a normal sized heart, and ECG shows normal sinus rhythm with no evidence of ventricular enlargement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Seizures","Congenital cardiac disease","Gastro-oesophageal reflux disease","Submucous cleft of the soft palate","Oesophageal atresia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal atresia\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this scenario. Oesophageal atresia often presents in the neonatal period with episodes of cyanosis and respiratory distress during or after feeding, as milk cannot pass into the stomach and may be aspirated. The absence of antenatal care increases the risk of undetected congenital anomalies, and the normal chest X-ray and ECG do not exclude this diagnosis. The intermittent nature of the cyanosis, its association with feeding, and the lack of other findings make oesophageal atresia the most probable cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeizures\u003C/strong\u003E are unlikely to present with isolated cyanosis without other neurological features such as abnormal movements, altered tone, or changes in consciousness. Neonatal seizures typically have additional clinical signs that would be apparent on examination or observation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECongenital cardiac disease\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with persistent rather than intermittent cyanosis, and is often associated with abnormal findings on chest X-ray or ECG. The normal investigations and the episodic nature of the symptoms make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastro-oesophageal reflux disease\u003C/strong\u003E is common in neonates and can cause regurgitation or mild distress after feeds, but it rarely causes significant cyanosis. The presence of central cyanosis after feeding should prompt consideration of more serious structural causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubmucous cleft of the soft palate\u003C/strong\u003E may cause feeding difficulties but is less likely to cause central cyanosis. It is also typically associated with other signs such as a nasal quality to the cry, nasal regurgitation, and in older infants, recurrent otitis media from Eustachian tube dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOesophageal atresia should be suspected in any neonate with feeding-associated cyanosis, especially in the absence of antenatal care. Early recognition and surgical referral are essential to prevent complications such as aspiration and malnutrition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oesophageal atresia commonly presents in neonates with episodes of cyanosis and respiratory distress during or after feeding.","Absence of antenatal care increases the risk of undetected congenital anomalies such as oesophageal atresia.","Normal chest X-ray and ECG do not exclude oesophageal atresia, which may present with intermittent symptoms related to feeding."],"references":["Kliegman R, Stanton B, St Geme JW, Schor NF, Behrman RE, editors. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics. 20th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2015. p. 1757\u201365.","Rintala RJ, Pakarinen MP. Esophageal atresia: clinical presentation and diagnosis. Semin Pediatr Surg. 2019 Feb;28(1):14-20. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1053/j.sempedsurg.2018.11.007","Kovesi T, Rubin S. Long-term complications of congenital esophageal atresia and/or tracheoesophageal fistula. Chest. 2019 May;155(5):1014-1022. Available from: https://doi.org/10.1016/j.chest.2018.11.040"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85922"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T09:31:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-01T18:50:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2710"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103500"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"351","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/351"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Gastroesophageal reflux","synonyms":["GORD","Gastroesophageal reflux dis